definition.value: A HEPES that is ethanesulfonic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is replaced by a 4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-yl group. A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 7.55 at 20 degreeC.

An erythromycin that consists of erythronolide A having 2,6-dideoxy-3-C-methyl-3-O-methyl-alpha-L-ribo-hexopyranosyl and 3,4,6-trideoxy-3-(dimethylamino)-beta-D-xylo-hexopyranosyl residues attahced at positions 4 and 6 respectively.
A very long-chain fatty acid that is tricosane in which one of the methyl groups has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.
The pyranose form of D-tagatose.
A straight-chain, fifteen-carbon carboxylic acid with no heteroatoms; a long-chain of mainly ruminant origin.
An L-fucopyranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A D-fucopyranose having alpha-configuration at its anomeric centre.
A L-fucopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
The pyranose form of D-quinovose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position .
An aromatic amino acid consisting of anthranilic acid carrying an N-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl substituent. An analgesic and anti-inflammatory, it is used in rheumatic disorders.
An aminobenzoic acid carrying an amino group at position 3.
The open chain form of D-glucose.
An aminoglycoside antibiotic produced by Micromonospora rhodorangea. It blocks polypeptide synthesis  by inhibiting the elongation step in both prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells.
An aminocarboxamidine, the parent compound of the guanidines.
A L-galactopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric center.
An aldoheptose in pyranose cyclic form with L-glycero-alpha-D-manno stereochemistry.
Riboflavin in which the nitrogen at position 5 is replaced by CH and the methyl groups at positions 7 and 8 are substituted by hydrogen and hydroxy, respectively.
A straight-chain alkane with seven carbon atoms. It has been found in Jeffrey pine (Pinus jeffreyi).
An optically active form of alloisoleucine having L-(2S,3R)-configuration.
A phosphate ion that is the conjugate base of dihydrogenphosphate.
An  indol-3-yl carboxylic acid that is  propionic acid substituted by a 1H-indol-3-yl group at position 3.
A straight chain alkane composed of 20 carbon atoms. It has been isolated from the leaves of Agave attenuata.
A compound showing yellow-green fluorescence, formed by a photolysis of riboflavin in alkaline solution.
A L-fructofuranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
A branched-chain saturated fatty acid consisting of tridecanoic acid carrying a 12-methyl group.
The (S)-enantiomer of lipoic acid. Not found in nature, it may exert detrimental effects on biosystems.
An N-acyl-hexosamine that is the methyl alpha-glycoside of the terminal moiety, and presumed antigenic determinant, of the O-specific polysaccharide of Vibrio cholerae O:1, serotype Ogawa.

Tetracycline which lacks the methyl substituent at position 7 and in which the hydrogen para- to the phenolic hydroxy group is substituted by chlorine. Like tetracycline, it is an antibiotic, but being excreted more slowly, effective blood levels are maintained for longer. It is used (mainly as the hydrochloride) for the treatment of Lyme disease, acne and bronchitis, as well as for hyponatraemia (low blood sodium concentration) due to the syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone (SIADH) where fluid restriction alone has been ineffective.
A L-xylopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
A methyl mannoside having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.

A carbapenemcarboxylic acid in which the azetidine and pyrroline rings carry 1-hydroxymethyl and in which the azetidine and pyrroline rings carry 1-hydroxymethyl and 5-(dimethylcarbamoyl)pyrrolidin-3-ylthio substituents respectively.
A menaquinone whose side-chain contains 8 isoprene units in an all-trans-configuration.
An N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminide having a methyl substituent at the anomeric position.
An iminium ion obtained by dimethylation of the imino group of 4-{[4-(dimethylamino)phenyl](phenyl)methylene}cyclohexa-2,5-dien-1-imine. Used in the form of its chloride salt as a green-coloured dye.
A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 7.2 at 20 degreeC.
A menaquinone whose side-chain contains 9 isoprene units in an all-trans-configuration.
A glycol that is the (S)-enantiomer of 2-methylpentane-2,4-diol.

A tetrahydronicotinamide adenine dinucleotide obtained by formal stereo- and regioselective hydration across the 5,6-double bond in the nicotinyl ring of NADH, with the hydroxy group located at position 6, having (S)-configuration.
A menaquinone whose side-chain contains seven isoprene units in an all-trans-configutation.
An N-acetyl-D-glucosamine that has alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A nucleotide in which the ribose moiety has one or more of its hydroxy groups substituted by hydrogen.
The alpha-anomer of N-acetyl-D-galactosamine 1-phosphate.

A semicarbazone resulting from the formal condensation of semicarbazide with 5-nitrofuraldehyde. A broad spectrum antibacterial drug, although with little activity against Pseudomonas species, it is used as a local application for burns, ulcers, wounds and skin infections.
A mucopolysaccharide consisting of repeating beta-(1->4)-linked L-iduronyl-(beta1->3)-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine units.
